  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "Let the limit be $L$. We have\n$$ L = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x) = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} x \\left( \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{x^2}{x^3} - \\frac{x^3}{x^3}} + 1 \\right) = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} x \\left( \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{1}{x} - 1} + 1 \\right) $$\nWe can write $\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3+x^2} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3(1-\\frac{1}{x})} = -x\\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}}$.\nThen we have\n$$ L = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x) = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( -x\\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} + x \\right) = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} x \\left( 1 - \\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} \\right) $$\nNow let $u = \\frac{1}{x}$. Then as $x \\to \\infty$, $u \\to 0$.\n$$ L = \\lim_{u\\to 0} \\frac{1 - \\sqrt[3]{1-u}}{u} $$\nNow let $f(u) = \\sqrt[3]{1-u}$. Then $f'(u) = \\frac{1}{3} (1-u)^{-2/3} (-1) = -\\frac{1}{3} (1-u)^{-2/3}$. Thus $f'(0) = -\\frac{1}{3}$.\n$$ L = \\lim_{u\\to 0} \\frac{1 - f(u)}{u} = \\lim_{u\\to 0} \\frac{f(0) - f(u)}{u} = -f'(0) = - \\left( -\\frac{1}{3} \\right) = \\frac{1}{3} $$\nThus, the limit is $\\frac{1}{3}$.\n\nAlternatively, we can use the identity $a^3 + b^3 = (a+b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)$. Let $a = \\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3}$ and $b = x$.\n$$ a^3 + b^3 = x^2 - x^3 + x^3 = x^2 $$\n$$ a+b = \\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3} + x $$\n$$ a^2 - ab + b^2 = (\\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3})^2 - x\\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3} + x^2 = \\sqrt[3]{(x^2-x^3)^2} - x\\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3} + x^2 $$\nThen\n$$ \\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3} + x = \\frac{a^3+b^3}{a^2-ab+b^2} = \\frac{x^2}{\\sqrt[3]{(x^2-x^3)^2} - x\\sqrt[3]{x^2-x^3} + x^2} $$\n$$ = \\frac{x^2}{\\sqrt[3]{x^6(1-\\frac{1}{x})^2} - x\\sqrt[3]{-x^3(1-\\frac{1}{x})} + x^2} = \\frac{x^2}{x^2\\sqrt[3]{(1-\\frac{1}{x})^2} - x(-x)\\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} + x^2} $$\n$$ = \\frac{x^2}{x^2\\sqrt[3]{(1-\\frac{1}{x})^2} + x^2\\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} + x^2} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt[3]{(1-\\frac{1}{x})^2} + \\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} + 1} $$\nAs $x\\to \\infty$, $\\frac{1}{x} \\to 0$.\n$$ \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt[3]{(1-\\frac{1}{x})^2} + \\sqrt[3]{1-\\frac{1}{x}} + 1} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt[3]{1^2} + \\sqrt[3]{1} + 1} = \\frac{1}{1+1+1} = \\frac{1}{3} $$\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{1/3}$",
